3. Smoke Testing Phase

Move to Smoke Testing.

“Once the build is installed, we run automated smoke tests to verify the environment is stable.”

“In our case, smoke testing includes executing key system jobs through the Tidal scheduler, which generates the required files or data outputs.”

“Smoke testing acts as a quick health check to ensure the system is functioning correctly before moving into deeper testing.”

“If the smoke test fails, the pipeline immediately flags the issue and creates a defect for the team.”

⸻

4. Regression Testing Phase (Main Automation)

Move to the UAT Environment section.

“Once smoke testing passes, the pipeline moves into automated regression validation within the UAT environment.”

“This is where our data automation framework performs deeper validation on the system outputs.”

First step:

“The framework verifies the file layout and structure, ensuring the generated files match the expected format.”

Next explain validation types:

“After layout validation, the framework performs automated comparisons depending on the output type.”

• File-to-File validation – comparing generated files against expected outputs
• File-to-Database validation – verifying that data loaded into the database matches the source file
• Table-to-Table validation – validating data transformations across system tables

Explain the process:

“The framework parses the generated data, temporarily stores it, and then connects to SQL Server to retrieve the corresponding database records.”

“It then performs automated comparisons across thousands of records to ensure the data is processed correctly.”

⸻

5. Test Results

Point to PASS / FAIL icons.

“If any mismatch is detected during validation, the pipeline fails and a defect is logged so the issue can be investigated.”

“If all validations pass, the pipeline marks the test results as successful.”

